It would be usefull to have a Version API in PDFBox. So 
that an application can print out the version number of 
PDFBox. E.g. most of the Apache projects have a 
Version class with some information. To retrieve this 
info, a static method or field should be accessed (no 
instantiation) so that a server application can just print 
all the version infos of it's libs without instantiations.



Example:


public final class Version {

    /** Build number (timestamp with format 
yyyyMMddHHmmssSSS). */
    static public final long BUILD = 
20050804194003805L; //automatically set during Ant 
compilation!
    /** Release date of this version (date format 
dd.MM.yyyy). */
    static public final String DATE 
= "04.08.2005"; //automatically set during Ant 
compilation!
    /**
     * Version number of format x.y.z, with
     * <ul>
     * <li>x = major version
     * <li>y = minor version
     * <li>z = bug fix version
     * </ul>
     */
    static public final String NUMBER = "2.2.0";
    /** Minimum JVM version required. */
    static public final String NUMBER_JAVAMIN = "1.5";
    /** Title of this project. */
    static public final String TITLE = "My supadupa Tools 
Library";


    /**
     * Print version information to system console 
(System.out) and in a Dialog.
     * 
     * @param args Not required.
     */
    static public void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(getAbout());
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, 
getAboutHTML(), "About", 
JOptionPane.INFORMATION_MESSAGE);
        System.exit(0);
    }//main()

    /**
     * Get about information of this project (plain text).
     * 
     * @return 'About' information.
     */
    static public String getAbout() {
        return TITLE + " "+NUMBER + " (Date: "+DATE+", 
build "+BUILD+") - (C) Master of teddies";
    }//getAbout()

    /**
     * Get about information of this project (HTML 
formatted). 
     *
     * @return 'About' information.
     */
    static public String getAboutHTML() {
        StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer
("<html><center><font size=+2>");
        sb.append(TITLE);
        sb.append("</font></center><br>Version: ");
        sb.append(NUMBER);
        sb.append("<br><font size=-2>(Date: ");
        sb.append(DATE);
        sb.append(", build: ");
        sb.append(BUILD);
        sb.append(")</font><br>Java required: ");
        sb.append(NUMBER_JAVAMIN);
        sb.append("<hr size=1>\u00a9 Master of 
teddies</html>");

        return sb.toString();
    }//getAbout()

}//Version



I use this in my projects and build the JARs to start this 
class as an application. This way, I just have to double 
click the JAR or call the Version class in a shell to get 
version info.

